instruction: [INST] Analyze this file to learn MacBook motherboard repair. The 'definitions' section explains key technical terms. The 'threads' section contains real-world repair discussions. Use both sections to understand and learn how to troubleshoot MacBook issues. Posts from username 'larossmann' , 'dukefawks' , and '2informaticos' are posts from trusted experts.[/INST]

definitions.820-00164: What is 820-00164? a LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER.
definitions.U1950: What is U1950? This chip often becomes corroded on pin 8 on the PP3V42_G3H pin causing PM_SLP_S4_L to go missing.

threads.title: <LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>820-00164</LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER> Everything is present but no post
threads.message: This board was hit in multiple spots by liquid. I included pre-ultrasonic-cleaning pictures. I replace the LCD connector. Board is not posting. All voltages are present the that I can possible think to check. Vcore is good. All <CHIP>U1950</CHIP> voltages are present and normal compared to a good board. S0 voltages are present. No chime. PRAM does nothing. I'm out of ideas.

threads.title: <LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>820-00164</LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER> Everything is present but no post
threads.message:
Pufff, I saw liquid sign on the MOSFETs from CPU power supply :(
If you don't find some corroded resistor/trace, on the board, could be dead CPU...

Try new BIOS, just in case.
Also check all SPi Bus series Termination resistors.
J6100 looks bad too, maybe need to remove it.

threads.title: <LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>820-00164</LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER> Everything is present but no post
threads.message: Any USB activity at all? If no, def try new BIOS and <CHIP>U6101</CHIP> could be one of them seeing you had corrosion there. Also assuming you definitely removed the JTAG
